-### CMS Considerations
-- All page content should be editable via the CMS — headlines, body copy, images, FAQ items, case study entries
-- Bookshop components should define clear, well-labeled fields so content can be updated without developer involvement
-- Case studies should be a content collection (Astro content collections or markdown files) so new ones can be added via CMS without code changes
-- FAQ items should be data-driven (YAML/JSON/markdown) so questions can be added, reordered, or removed via CMS
+- **Analytics:** Google Analytics 4
+- **Search:** Google Search Console
+
+### CMS Decision
+**Critical correction from v2:**
+Do **not** keep “Sveltia CMS or CloudCannon” unresolved indefinitely.
+
+Recommended v1 decision:
+- Build the site so content is structured and CMS-ready
+- Do **not** let CMS selection block launch
+- If no-code editing is required at launch, choose **CloudCannon**, because it has native Bookshop support and a stronger visual-editing path
+- If no-code editing is **not** required at launch, ship without a CMS and keep content in Astro content collections / data files until it becomes necessary
+
+**Why this is stronger:**
+A static agency site with a small number of core pages does not need CMS complexity to justify launch. The v2 plan treats CMS choice like a foundational requirement when it is really a secondary workflow decision.
+
+### Content Architecture
+Recommended structure:
+- global site settings in a single data file
+- page content in Astro content collections or front matter
+- FAQ items as data-driven content
+- case studies as their own collection
+- contact CTA parameters passed via query string
+- reusable sections mapped cleanly to Bookshop components
 
 ### Performance Requirements
-- We sell fast websites. Our own site better be fast. Target: 90+ on all Lighthouse categories.
-- No heavy JavaScript frameworks beyond what Astro requires. Use Astro's partial hydration — only hydrate interactive components (accordion, mobile nav, form validation).
-- Optimize all images: WebP format, responsive sizes via `<picture>` element, lazy loading below the fold.
-- Minimal external font loading — subset if possible, use `font-display: swap`.
-- Inline critical CSS. Defer non-critical styles.
+This site sells speed, so speed is part of the brand.
+
+Targets:
+- **90+ Lighthouse** on representative pages
+- strong **Core Web Vitals** in real-world conditions
+- no obvious lag on mid-range mobile devices
+
+Requirements:
+- Use Astro’s default low-JS approach
+- Hydrate only genuinely interactive elements
+- Use Astro image tooling (`<Image />` / `<Picture />`) for local assets
+- Serve responsive images
+- Lazy-load below-the-fold images
+- Avoid heavy embeds above the fold
+- Avoid unnecessary third-party widgets
+- Subset fonts and use `font-display: swap`
+- Inline or otherwise prioritize critical styles
+
+**Internal correction from v2:**
+A live Google Maps embed is often too heavy to deserve default inclusion. Use a lighter alternative unless the embed genuinely adds conversion value.
+
+### Forms & Spam Prevention
+- Netlify detects forms by parsing **static HTML at deploy time**
+- The form cannot be client-rendered only
+- Enable automatic form detection in Netlify
+- Add a honeypot immediately
+- Use a custom success page (`/thank-you`)
+- Test form detection after deploy, not just locally
+
+### Analytics & Tracking
+Base events to track:
+- `page_view`
+- `cta_click`
+- `phone_click`
+- `form_start`
+- `generate_lead`
+
+Recommendations:
+- mark `generate_lead` as a **key event**
+- capture source page and service intent
+- capture campaign parameters when available
+- keep naming consistent and simple
+- avoid event sprawl
+
+**Internal note:**
+Do not add Google Tag Manager by default unless it becomes necessary for ad pixels or more complex tag orchestration. For the v1 site, direct GA4 tagging may be simpler and lighter.
 
 ### SEO Baseline
-While aggressive SEO isn't the growth strategy (cold outreach is), the site should still follow best practices:
-- Unique title tags and meta descriptions per page
-- Proper heading hierarchy (one H1 per page)
-- Schema markup for local business (LocalBusiness type with service offerings)
-- Open Graph and Twitter card meta tags for link sharing (important for cold outreach — links shared in emails and DMs should preview well)
-- Sitemap.xml and robots.txt
-- Fast load times (covered above)
-- Alt text on all images
-- Canonical URLs on all pages
+Even if cold outreach remains the main acquisition channel, the site must still be technically solid.
+
+Requirements:
+- unique title tags and meta descriptions
+- one clear H1 per page
+- canonical URLs
+- sitemap
+- robots.txt
+- alt text on meaningful images
+- Open Graph meta tags
+- X / Twitter card tags
+- search-console-ready setup
+
+### Schema Markup
+**Critical correction from v2:**
+Do not default to broad **LocalBusiness** schema just because the business is local. Use schema that matches the real business model.
+
+Recommended approach:
+- **Organization** schema site-wide
+- **Service** schema on service pages where appropriate
+- **FAQPage** schema only where the FAQ is actually visible
+- Use **LocalBusiness** / **ProfessionalService** only if the public business-location data is accurate and appropriate to publish
 
 ### Accessibility Baseline
-- Sufficient color contrast ratios (especially orange text on dark backgrounds — test this; orange on navy may need to be adjusted for WCAG AA compliance)
-- Keyboard navigable forms and accordion
-- Proper ARIA labels on interactive elements (accordion buttons, mobile nav toggle, form fields)
-- Skip-to-content link
-- Form labels properly associated with inputs (not just placeholder text)
-- Focus states visible on all interactive elements
+- WCAG AA contrast minimum
+- visible focus states everywhere
+- semantic landmarks
+- skip-to-content link
+- keyboard-accessible nav and accordions
+- proper labels and error messaging on forms
+- `aria-expanded` / `aria-controls` where appropriate
+- mobile menu focus management
+- respect `prefers-reduced-motion`
+
+### Security / Ops
+Recommended baseline:
+- basic security headers via Netlify
+- domain-matched business email address (not a throwaway Gmail on the public site)
+- backup inbox for form notifications
+- documented access to:
+  - Netlify
+  - domain registrar
+  - GA4
+  - Search Console
+  - DNS
 
